{"title_page": "Edir Macedo", "text_new": "{{short description|Brazilian evangelical pastor}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{Cleanup rewrite|date=November 2009}}\n{{POV|date=May 2015}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n|name         = Edir Macedo\n|image        = Edir Macedo2007.jpg\n|image_size   = \n|caption      = Edir Macedo in 2007\n|birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1945|02|18}}\n|birth_place  = [[Rio das Flores]], [[Rio de Janeiro|RJ]], Brazil\n|occupation   = Businessman, preacher, theologian, and author\n|net worth    = US$1.1&nbsp;billion<ref name=\"Forbes profile\">{{cite web |title=Forbes profile: Edir Macedo |url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/edir-macedo/ |website=Forbes |accessdate=November 5, 2018}}</ref>\n|nationality  = Brazilian\n|website      = [http://blogs.universal.org/bispomacedo/ universal.org/bispomacedo]\n}}\n\n'''Edir Macedo Bezerra''' (born February 18, 1945) is a Brazilian [[evangelical]] bishop, writer, billionaire businessman,<ref name=forbes/><ref name=\"Forbes profile\"/> and the founder of the [[Universal Church of the Kingdom of God]] (UCKG).<ref name=istoe>{{cite web|url=http://www.bispomacedo.com.br/2009/10/27/o-ateu-que-nao-vive-sem-deus/|title=O ateu que n\u00e3o vive sem Deus|work=The Blog of Edir Macedo |accessdate=21 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.istoe.com.br/reportagens/256085_O+CEU+E+O+INFERNO+NAO+SAO+FOLCLORE+|title=O c\u00e9u e o inferno n\u00e3o s\u00e3o folclore|work=istoe.com.br|accessdate=29 January 2013}}</ref> He is the owner and chairman of the second-largest television network in Brazil, [[RecordTV]], since 1989 with the [[Grupo Record]], which he founded after he bought the network.\n\n== Early life ==\nEdir Macedo was born in Rio de Janeiro in 1945 (one of seven surviving children).<ref name=UCKG />\n\nAccording to Macedo's website<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bispomacedo.com.br/en/biography/|title=Biography \u2013 Bishop Macedo|website=bispomacedo.com.br|accessdate=November 5, 2018}}</ref> he holds a doctor's degree in Theology and in Christian Philosophy, and an honorary degree in Divinity from the Faculdade de Educa\u00e7\u00e3o Teol\u00f3gica do Estado de S\u00e3o Paulo.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://translate.google.com/translate?sl=auto&tl=en&js=n&prev=_t&hl=en&ie=UTF-8&eotf=1&u=http://www.faculdadeteologica.com.br/doutorado/teologia/&act=url|title=Google Translate|publisher=Google|accessdate=November 5, 2018}}</ref>{{Failed verification|date=March 2013}} He also received a masters in theological science through the [[Federation of Evangelical Religious Entities of Spain]] in Madrid, Spain.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}}\n\n==Career==\nIn 1963 he began a career as a civil servant, initially working with the state-run lottery of Rio de Janeiro, Loterj, and also at the Brazilian Institute of Geography and Statistics, IBGE, as a researcher in the economic census of 1970.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}}\n\nMacedo was raised [[Catholic]], but by 1965 converted to [[Pentecostalism]], after an invitation from his sister to [greja Crist\u00e3 de Nova Vida.<ref>CORTEN Andr\u00e9, DOZON Jean-Pierre, ORO Ari Pedro, ''Les nouveaux conqu\u00e9rants de la foi-L'Eglise universelle du royaume de Dieu (Br\u00e9sil)'', KARTHALA Editions, France, 2003, p. 46</ref><ref name=UCKG>{{Cite book|last1=Leonard|first1=Jim|url=http://www.comingstobrazil.com/blog/UNIVERSAL%20CHURCH%20OF%20THE%20KINGDOM%20OF%20GOD.pdf|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304104041/http://www.comingstobrazil.com/blog/UNIVERSAL%20CHURCH%20OF%20THE%20KINGDOM%20OF%20GOD.pdf|archive-date=March 4, 2016|title=Universal Church of the Kingdom of God|publisher=[[Faith Baptist Bible College and Theological Seminary|Faith Baptist Theological Seminary]]|location=[[Ankeny, Iowa]]|date=May 8, 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 1975, Macedo founded a Pentecostal church with [[Romildo Ribeiro Soares]], Cruzada do Caminho Eterno. After an argument, the two separated.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}}\n\nIn 1977, Macedo founded with others the [[Universal Church of the Kingdom of God]] in Rio de Janeiro state, Brazil.<ref>Patrice de Plunkett, ''Les \u00e9vang\u00e9liques \u00e0 la conqu\u00eate du monde'', \u00c9ditions Perrin, France, 2009, p. 110</ref>\n\nIn 1989 he bought the [[free-to-air]] commercial television network RecordTV and in the same year he founded Grupo Record. In 2007 he founded the 24-hour free-to-air news channel Record News.\n\nHis rapidly growing religious movement and his teaching of [[prosperity theology]] have been a source of controversy. His sermons partly focus on freeing his followers from [[unclean spirits]] that oppress them, which manifest in them, and are cast out in the name of Jesus, for them to overcome their problems.<ref name=\"Pastor misusing funds\">{{cite news|last1=Preston|first1=Julia|title=Brazil's Pastor of Prosperity Accused of Misusing Funds|work=The Washington Post|date=August 3, 1991}}</ref> His views about other faiths, particularly Catholicism, are also controversial. In 1992 he spent eleven days in jail on accusations of [[charlatanism]]. There were several protests, with his religious followers camping in front of the police precinct he was held in, according to his autobiography \"Nothing to Lose\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uckg.org/uk/?p=49898|title=uk \u2013 UCKG HelpCentre|website=uckg.org|accessdate=November 5, 2018}}</ref> His prosperity theology is used by church leaders to justify his lifestyle, \"If I preach prosperity and my clothes are ragged, who will follow me?\"<ref name=\"Pastor misusing funds\" />\n\nFrom March 2013 to 2015, Macedo has been on the [[Forbes billionaires list]] with a reported US$1.1&nbsp;billion, and $1.24&nbsp;b for Macedo and family, making him by far the richest pastor in Brazil and the world.<ref name=forbes>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/andersonantunes/2013/01/17/the-richest-pastors-in-brazil/|title=The Richest Pastors in Brazil|first=Anderson|last=Antunes|website=Forbes|accessdate=November 5, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Forbes profile\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/andersonantunes/2015/03/02/brazils-richest-people-facts-and-figures/ |title=Brazil's Richest People: Facts and Figures |newspaper=Forbes |date=March 2, 2015 |author=Anderson Antunes |accessdate= August 22, 2017}}</ref> He was not on the list for 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/kenrapoza/2016/07/17/who-wants-to-be-a-brazilian-billionaire/ |title=Who Wants To Be A Brazilian Billionaire? |newspaper=Forbes |date=July 17, 2016 |author=Kenneth Rapoza |accessdate= August 22, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe UCKG built a US$300&nbsp;million [[Temple of Solomon (S\u00e3o Paulo)|replica of Solomon's Temple in S\u00e3o Paulo]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ariquemesonline.com.br/noticia.asp?cod=292351&codDep=30 |title=Igreja Universal do Reino de Deus inaugura empreendimento fara\u00f4nico de R$685 milh\u00f5es|language=Portuguese|trans-title=Universal Church of the Kingdom of God inaugurates R$685&nbsp;million Pharaonic enterprise|website=Ariquemes Online |date=August 1, 2014 |accessdate= August 19, 2019}}</ref> Macedo and the UCKG have an $8&nbsp;million contract to import stones from Israel like those used to build the temple in Israel.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.jpost.com/International/First-Temple-replica-to-be-built-in-Sao-Paulo |title=First Temple replica to be built in Sao Paulo |newspaper=The Jerusalem Post |date=July 27, 2010  |author=GIL STERN STERN SHEFLER |accessdate= August 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMacedo is married to Ester Bezerra, and has two daughters, Cristiane and Viviane, and an adopted son, Moises.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}}\n\n==Controversies==\n\n===Opposition to interracial marriage===\n\nMacedo was criticized for writing an article opposing [[interracial marriage]]. He tried to justify his views claiming that [[multiracial]] children should be avoided because they will suffer discrimination.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.odia.com.br/_conteudo/noticia/brasil/2014-08-18/bispo-macedo-nao-recomenda-casamento-entre-pessoas-de-racas-diferentes.html|title=Bispo Macedo n\u00e3o recomenda casamento entre pessoas de 'ra\u00e7as diferentes'|first=O.|last=Dia|date=August 18, 2014|website=O Dia \u2013 _legado_Brasil|accessdate=February 1, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://noticias.gospelmais.com.br/bispo-macedo-homens-casar-mulheres-raca-diferente-39342.html|title=Macedo: homens n\u00e3o devem casar com mulheres de ra\u00e7as diferentes|date=July 16, 2012|website=Not\u00edcias Gospel|accessdate=February 1, 2019}}</ref> This led to several accusations of racism and [[misogyny]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://veja.abril.com.br/blog/reinaldo/edir-macedo-racismo-e-misoginia-cade-os-ministros-da-igualdade-racial-e-das-mulheres/|title=Edir Macedo, racismo e misoginia: cad\u00ea os ministros da Igualdade Racial e das Mulheres? \u2013 Reinaldo Azevedo|website=VEJA.com|accessdate=February 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Religious intolerance===\n\nMacedo has been criticised, especially after the [[Chute na santa incident|'kicking of the saint' incident]] in which UCKG bishop S\u00e9rgio Von Helder, who later left the Church, kicked a Catholic icon in a TV program, for which he was later imprisoned for two years.<ref>{{YouTube|mlmoWbHgqr0|Kicking off the catholic simbol}}</ref> He also authored a book called ''Orix\u00e1s, Caboclos and Guias'' in which he attacks [[Afro-Brazilian religion]], accusing it of [[Satanism]] and \"the root of all of Brazil's troubles\". The book was first prohibited as [[hate speech]], but after legal efforts from Macedo's church it was allowed for the sake of [[free speech]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://expresso-noticia.jusbrasil.com.br/noticias/136368/trf-libera-circulacao-do-livro-de-edir-macedo|title=TRF libera circula\u00e7\u00e3o do livro de Edir Macedo|website=Jusbrasil|accessdate=February 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Federal Justice indictment===\n\nEdir Macedo was indicted by the Federal Justice for import of equipment and use of public documents and legal proceedings, but not convicted. Ten years later he was prosecuted again by the prosecutors of the State of S\u00e3o Paulo. On October 19, 2010 the S\u00e3o Paulo Justice Court (TJ-SP) annulled all accusations made by the S\u00e3o Paulo Public Ministry against the UCKG and its principal representatives by a majority vote. The judges deemed that the S\u00e3o Paulo prosecutors did not have jurisdiction to investigate the case, as the accusations were of a type that fell into the federal jurisdiction.<ref>[http://www.universopolitico.com/exibir.php?noticia=7805 Universo Politico: Accusations against UCKG recognised as illegal, 24 October 2010] {{in lang|pt}}</ref>\n\n==Companies==\n{{BLP sources section|date=March 2013}}\nMacedo also leads [[Rede Record]]<ref name=istoe/> (the second biggest television network in Brazil), [[Rede Fam\u00edlia]], [[Record News]], [[Line Records]], 64 radio stations of [[Rede Aleluia]] and [[Universal Produ\u00e7\u00f5es]].\n\n==Books==\nTen million copies of evangelical books by Macedo have been sold, and over 34 titles published. Titles include ''Orix\u00e1s, Caboclos and Guias'' and ''In the Footsteps of Jesus'', both of which sold more than three million copies in Brazil. He has also sold his trilogy called ''Nada a perder'' (''Nothing to lose''), with millions of copies sold worldwide. He has written several religious books including the polemical best-seller ''Orix\u00e1s, Caboclos e Guias, Deuses ou Dem\u00f4nios''.\n\n==Movies==\nHis broadcasting company Record financed the 2018 movie ''Nada a perder'' (''[[Nothing to lose (2018)|Nothing to Lose]]'') about Edir Macedo's life, which is based on his autobiography. Reviews were negative, called it a glorification. Tickets are given out for free at the churches to make it a box office success, a practice already known from [[The Ten Commandments: The Movie|a previous movie]] by Record.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/may/15/nothing-to-lose-nada-a-perder-brazil-sold-out-empty-cinemas-universal-church 'It is strange': Brazilian church blockbuster plays to empty cinemas], Dom Phillips, ''[[The Guardian]]'', May 16, 2018</ref> A second part is announced for 2019.<ref>[https://www1.folha.uol.com.br/ilustrada/2018/05/filme-sobre-edir-macedo-se-torna-a-maior-bilheteria-do-cinema-brasileiro.shtml Filme sobre Edir Macedo se torna a maior bilheteria do cinema brasileiro], Tiago Dias, [[Folha de S.Paulo]], May 7, 2018 (Portuguese)</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[:pt:O Bispo - A Hist\u00f3ria Revelada de Edir Macedo|''The Bishop \u2013 revealed history of Edir Macedo'']]: biography {{in lang|pt}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050907234745/http://www.bispomacedo.com.br/ Bispo Macedo] \u2013 Edir Macedo's website {{in lang|pt}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{Portal|Evangelical Christianity|}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Macedo, Edir}}\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:Brazilian television evangelists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Former Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Brazilian Pentecostal pastors]]\n[[Category:Universal Church of the Kingdom of God]]\n[[Category:Prosperity theologians]]\n[[Category:Brazilian mass media owners]]\n[[Category:Brazilian billionaires]]\n[[Category:Converts to Pentecostal denominations]]\n[[Category:Critics of the Catholic Church]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Brazilian evangelical pastor}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{Cleanup rewrite|date=November 2009}}\n{{POV|date=May 2015}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n|name         = Edir Macedo\n|image        = Edir Macedo2007.jpg\n|image_size   = \n|caption      = Edir Macedo in 2007\n|birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1945|02|18}}\n|birth_place  = [[Rio das Flores]], [[Rio de Janeiro|RJ]], Brazil\n|occupation   = Businessman, preacher, theologian, and author\n|net worth    = US$1.1&nbsp;billion<ref name=\"Forbes profile\">{{cite web |title=Forbes profile: Edir Macedo |url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/edir-macedo/ |website=Forbes |accessdate=November 5, 2018}}</ref>\n|nationality  = Brazilian\n|website      = [http://blogs.universal.org/bispomacedo/ universal.org/bispomacedo]\n}}\n\n'''Edir Macedo Bezerra''' (born February 18, 1945) is a Brazilian [[evangelical]] bishop, writer, billionaire businessman,<ref name=forbes/><ref name=\"Forbes profile\"/> and the founder of the [[Universal Church of the Kingdom of God]] (UCKG).<ref name=istoe>{{cite web|url=http://www.bispomacedo.com.br/2009/10/27/o-ateu-que-nao-vive-sem-deus/|title=O ateu que n\u00e3o vive sem Deus|work=The Blog of Edir Macedo |accessdate=21 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.istoe.com.br/reportagens/256085_O+CEU+E+O+INFERNO+NAO+SAO+FOLCLORE+|title=O c\u00e9u e o inferno n\u00e3o s\u00e3o folclore|work=istoe.com.br|accessdate=29 January 2013}}</ref> He is the owner and chairman of the second-largest television network in Brazil, [[RecordTV]], since 1989 with the [[Grupo Record]], which he founded after he bought the network.\n\n== Early life ==\nEdir Macedo was born in Rio de Janeiro in 1945 (one of seven surviving children).<ref name=UCKG />\n\nAccording to Macedo's website<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bispomacedo.com.br/en/biography/|title=Biography \u2013 Bishop Macedo|website=bispomacedo.com.br|accessdate=November 5, 2018}}</ref> he holds a doctor's degree in Theology and in Christian Philosophy, and an honorary degree in Divinity from the Faculdade de Educa\u00e7\u00e3o Teol\u00f3gica do Estado de S\u00e3o Paulo.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://translate.google.com/translate?sl=auto&tl=en&js=n&prev=_t&hl=en&ie=UTF-8&eotf=1&u=http://www.faculdadeteologica.com.br/doutorado/teologia/&act=url|title=Google Translate|publisher=Google|accessdate=November 5, 2018}}</ref>{{Failed verification|date=March 2013}} He also received a masters in theological science through the [[Federation of Evangelical Religious Entities of Spain]] in Madrid, Spain.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}}\n\n==Career==\nIn 1963 he began a career as a civil servant, initially working with the state-run lottery of Rio de Janeiro, Loterj, and also at the Brazilian Institute of Geography and Statistics, IBGE, as a researcher in the economic census of 1970.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}}\n\nMacedo was raised [[Catholic]], but by 1965 converted to [[Pentecostalism]], after an invitation from his sister to [[Igreja Crist\u00e3 de Nova Vida]].<ref>CORTEN Andr\u00e9, DOZON Jean-Pierre, ORO Ari Pedro, ''Les nouveaux conqu\u00e9rants de la foi-L'Eglise universelle du royaume de Dieu (Br\u00e9sil)'', KARTHALA Editions, France, 2003, p. 46</ref><ref name=UCKG>{{Cite book|last1=Leonard|first1=Jim|url=http://www.comingstobrazil.com/blog/UNIVERSAL%20CHURCH%20OF%20THE%20KINGDOM%20OF%20GOD.pdf|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304104041/http://www.comingstobrazil.com/blog/UNIVERSAL%20CHURCH%20OF%20THE%20KINGDOM%20OF%20GOD.pdf|archive-date=March 4, 2016|title=Universal Church of the Kingdom of God|publisher=[[Faith Baptist Bible College and Theological Seminary|Faith Baptist Theological Seminary]]|location=[[Ankeny, Iowa]]|date=May 8, 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 1975, Macedo founded a Pentecostal church with [[Romildo Ribeiro Soares]], Cruzada do Caminho Eterno. After an argument, the two separated.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}}\n\nIn 1977, Macedo founded with others the [[Universal Church of the Kingdom of God]] in Rio de Janeiro state, Brazil.<ref>Patrice de Plunkett, ''Les \u00e9vang\u00e9liques \u00e0 la conqu\u00eate du monde'', \u00c9ditions Perrin, France, 2009, p. 110</ref>\n\nIn 1989 he bought the [[free-to-air]] commercial television network RecordTV and in the same year he founded Grupo Record. In 2007 he founded the 24-hour free-to-air news channel Record News.\n\nHis rapidly growing religious movement and his teaching of [[prosperity theology]] have been a source of controversy. His sermons partly focus on freeing his followers from [[unclean spirits]] that oppress them, which manifest in them, and are cast out in the name of Jesus, for them to overcome their problems.<ref name=\"Pastor misusing funds\">{{cite news|last1=Preston|first1=Julia|title=Brazil's Pastor of Prosperity Accused of Misusing Funds|work=The Washington Post|date=August 3, 1991}}</ref> His views about other faiths, particularly Catholicism, are also controversial. In 1992 he spent eleven days in jail on accusations of [[charlatanism]]. There were several protests, with his religious followers camping in front of the police precinct he was held in, according to his autobiography \"Nothing to Lose\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uckg.org/uk/?p=49898|title=uk \u2013 UCKG HelpCentre|website=uckg.org|accessdate=November 5, 2018}}</ref> His prosperity theology is used by church leaders to justify his lifestyle, \"If I preach prosperity and my clothes are ragged, who will follow me?\"<ref name=\"Pastor misusing funds\" />\n\nFrom March 2013 to 2015, Macedo has been on the [[Forbes billionaires list]] with a reported US$1.1&nbsp;billion, and $1.24&nbsp;b for Macedo and family, making him by far the richest pastor in Brazil and the world.<ref name=forbes>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/andersonantunes/2013/01/17/the-richest-pastors-in-brazil/|title=The Richest Pastors in Brazil|first=Anderson|last=Antunes|website=Forbes|accessdate=November 5, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Forbes profile\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/andersonantunes/2015/03/02/brazils-richest-people-facts-and-figures/ |title=Brazil's Richest People: Facts and Figures |newspaper=Forbes |date=March 2, 2015 |author=Anderson Antunes |accessdate= August 22, 2017}}</ref> He was not on the list for 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/kenrapoza/2016/07/17/who-wants-to-be-a-brazilian-billionaire/ |title=Who Wants To Be A Brazilian Billionaire? |newspaper=Forbes |date=July 17, 2016 |author=Kenneth Rapoza |accessdate= August 22, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe UCKG built a US$300&nbsp;million [[Temple of Solomon (S\u00e3o Paulo)|replica of Solomon's Temple in S\u00e3o Paulo]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ariquemesonline.com.br/noticia.asp?cod=292351&codDep=30 |title=Igreja Universal do Reino de Deus inaugura empreendimento fara\u00f4nico de R$685 milh\u00f5es|language=Portuguese|trans-title=Universal Church of the Kingdom of God inaugurates R$685&nbsp;million Pharaonic enterprise|website=Ariquemes Online |date=August 1, 2014 |accessdate= August 19, 2019}}</ref> Macedo and the UCKG have an $8&nbsp;million contract to import stones from Israel like those used to build the temple in Israel.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.jpost.com/International/First-Temple-replica-to-be-built-in-Sao-Paulo |title=First Temple replica to be built in Sao Paulo |newspaper=The Jerusalem Post |date=July 27, 2010  |author=GIL STERN STERN SHEFLER |accessdate= August 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMacedo is married to Ester Bezerra, and has two daughters, Cristiane and Viviane, and an adopted son, Moises.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}}\n\n==Controversies==\n\n===Opposition to interracial marriage===\n\nMacedo was criticized for writing an article opposing [[interracial marriage]]. He tried to justify his views claiming that [[multiracial]] children should be avoided because they will suffer discrimination.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.odia.com.br/_conteudo/noticia/brasil/2014-08-18/bispo-macedo-nao-recomenda-casamento-entre-pessoas-de-racas-diferentes.html|title=Bispo Macedo n\u00e3o recomenda casamento entre pessoas de 'ra\u00e7as diferentes'|first=O.|last=Dia|date=August 18, 2014|website=O Dia \u2013 _legado_Brasil|accessdate=February 1, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://noticias.gospelmais.com.br/bispo-macedo-homens-casar-mulheres-raca-diferente-39342.html|title=Macedo: homens n\u00e3o devem casar com mulheres de ra\u00e7as diferentes|date=July 16, 2012|website=Not\u00edcias Gospel|accessdate=February 1, 2019}}</ref> This led to several accusations of racism and [[misogyny]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://veja.abril.com.br/blog/reinaldo/edir-macedo-racismo-e-misoginia-cade-os-ministros-da-igualdade-racial-e-das-mulheres/|title=Edir Macedo, racismo e misoginia: cad\u00ea os ministros da Igualdade Racial e das Mulheres? \u2013 Reinaldo Azevedo|website=VEJA.com|accessdate=February 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Religious intolerance===\n\nMacedo has been criticised, especially after the [[Chute na santa incident|'kicking of the saint' incident]] in which UCKG bishop S\u00e9rgio Von Helder, who later left the Church, kicked a Catholic icon in a TV program, for which he was later imprisoned for two years.<ref>{{YouTube|mlmoWbHgqr0|Kicking off the catholic simbol}}</ref> He also authored a book called ''Orix\u00e1s, Caboclos and Guias'' in which he attacks [[Afro-Brazilian religion]], accusing it of [[Satanism]] and \"the root of all of Brazil's troubles\". The book was first prohibited as [[hate speech]], but after legal efforts from Macedo's church it was allowed for the sake of [[free speech]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://expresso-noticia.jusbrasil.com.br/noticias/136368/trf-libera-circulacao-do-livro-de-edir-macedo|title=TRF libera circula\u00e7\u00e3o do livro de Edir Macedo|website=Jusbrasil|accessdate=February 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Federal Justice indictment===\n\nEdir Macedo was indicted by the Federal Justice for import of equipment and use of public documents and legal proceedings, but not convicted. Ten years later he was prosecuted again by the prosecutors of the State of S\u00e3o Paulo. On October 19, 2010 the S\u00e3o Paulo Justice Court (TJ-SP) annulled all accusations made by the S\u00e3o Paulo Public Ministry against the UCKG and its principal representatives by a majority vote. The judges deemed that the S\u00e3o Paulo prosecutors did not have jurisdiction to investigate the case, as the accusations were of a type that fell into the federal jurisdiction.<ref>[http://www.universopolitico.com/exibir.php?noticia=7805 Universo Politico: Accusations against UCKG recognised as illegal, 24 October 2010] {{in lang|pt}}</ref>\n\n==Companies==\n{{BLP sources section|date=March 2013}}\nMacedo also leads [[Rede Record]]<ref name=istoe/> (the second biggest television network in Brazil), [[Rede Fam\u00edlia]], [[Record News]], [[Line Records]], 64 radio stations of [[Rede Aleluia]] and [[Universal Produ\u00e7\u00f5es]].\n\n==Books==\nTen million copies of evangelical books by Macedo have been sold, and over 34 titles published. Titles include ''Orix\u00e1s, Caboclos and Guias'' and ''In the Footsteps of Jesus'', both of which sold more than three million copies in Brazil. He has also sold his trilogy called ''Nada a perder'' (''Nothing to lose''), with millions of copies sold worldwide. He has written several religious books including the polemical best-seller ''Orix\u00e1s, Caboclos e Guias, Deuses ou Dem\u00f4nios''.\n\n==Movies==\nHis broadcasting company Record financed the 2018 movie ''Nada a perder'' (''[[Nothing to lose (2018)|Nothing to Lose]]'') about Edir Macedo's life, which is based on his autobiography. Reviews were negative, called it a glorification. Tickets are given out for free at the churches to make it a box office success, a practice already known from [[The Ten Commandments: The Movie|a previous movie]] by Record.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/may/15/nothing-to-lose-nada-a-perder-brazil-sold-out-empty-cinemas-universal-church 'It is strange': Brazilian church blockbuster plays to empty cinemas], Dom Phillips, ''[[The Guardian]]'', May 16, 2018</ref> A second part is announced for 2019.<ref>[https://www1.folha.uol.com.br/ilustrada/2018/05/filme-sobre-edir-macedo-se-torna-a-maior-bilheteria-do-cinema-brasileiro.shtml Filme sobre Edir Macedo se torna a maior bilheteria do cinema brasileiro], Tiago Dias, [[Folha de S.Paulo]], May 7, 2018 (Portuguese)</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[:pt:O Bispo - A Hist\u00f3ria Revelada de Edir Macedo|''The Bishop \u2013 revealed history of Edir Macedo'']]: biography {{in lang|pt}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050907234745/http://www.bispomacedo.com.br/ Bispo Macedo] \u2013 Edir Macedo's website {{in lang|pt}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{Portal|Evangelical Christianity|}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Macedo, Edir}}\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:Brazilian television evangelists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Former Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Brazilian Pentecostal pastors]]\n[[Category:Universal Church of the Kingdom of God]]\n[[Category:Prosperity theologians]]\n[[Category:Brazilian mass media owners]]\n[[Category:Brazilian billionaires]]\n[[Category:Converts to Pentecostal denominations]]\n[[Category:Critics of the Catholic Church]]\n", "name_user": "Fabr\u00edcio Alenccar Araujos", "label": "safe", "comment": "making text correction", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edir_Macedo"}
{"title_page": "Plumhoff v. Rickard", "text_new": "{{Infobox SCOTUS case\n| Litigants = Plumoff v. Rickard\n| ArgueDate = March 4\n| ArgueYear = 2014\n| DecideDate = May 27\n| DecideYear = 2014\n| FullName = Officer Vance Plumhoff, et al., v. Whitne Rickard, a minor child, individually, and as surviving daughter of Donald Rickard, deceased, by and through her mother, Samantha Rickard, as parent and next friend\n| USVol = 572\n| USPage = ___\n| ParallelCitations = \n| Docket = 12-1117\n| OralArgument = https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/roberts6/oral_argument_audio/23632\n| OralReargument = \n| OpinionAnnouncement = https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/roberts6/opinion_announcement_audio/23622\n| Prior = \n| Subsequent = \n| Holding = (1) The [[Sixth Circuit]] properly exercised jurisdiction under 28 U. S. C. \u00a71291. The general rule that an order denying a summary judgment motion is not a \"final decision\", and thus not immediately appealable, does not apply when it is based on a qualified immunity claim. (2) The officers' conduct did not violate the [[Fourth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Fourth Amendment]].\n| SCOTUS = \n| Majority = Alito\n| JoinMajority = ''unanimous'' except Ginsburg as to parts III\u2013A and III\u2013B and Breyer as to part III\u2013B\u20132{{efn|name=opinionbreakdown}}\n| Concurrence = \n| JoinConcurrence = \n| Concurrence2 = \n| JoinConcurrence2 = \n| Concurrence/Dissent = \n| JoinConcurrence/Dissent = \n| Dissent = \n| JoinDissent = \n| Dissent2 = \n| JoinDissent2 = \n| LawsApplied = [[Fourth Amendment to the United States Constitution|U.S. Const. amend. IV]]\n}}\n\n'''''Plumhoff v. Rickard''''', 572 U.S. ___ (2014), is a [[Supreme Court of the United States|United States Supreme Court]] case involving the [[use of force]] by [[police officer]]s during high-speed [[car chase]]s. After first holding that it had [[jurisdiction]] to hear the case, the Court held that the conduct of the police officers involved in the case did not violate the [[Fourth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Fourth Amendment to the U.S. Constitution]], which prohibits unreasonable [[Search and seizure|searches and seizures]].\n\nAt midnight on July 18, 2004, Donald Rickard led police officers on a high-speed car chase which ended in a parking lot, where officers fired fifteen shots into Rickard's car. Rickard and his passenger both died from a combination of gunshot wounds and injuries sustained when the car eventually crashed. Rickard's daughter sued the officers who shot Rickard, arguing that they had used [[excessive force]] in violation of the Fourth Amendment. The officers moved for [[summary judgment]] based on [[qualified immunity]] because they believed their actions did not violate clearly established law at the time of the car chase. The district court denied this motion, and the court of appeals affirmed.\n\nOn May 27, 2014, the Supreme Court reversed, holding that the officers did not violate the Fourth Amendment. In a unanimous (9\u20130) decision authored by [[Justice Samuel Alito]],{{efn|name=opinionbreakdown}} the Court found that Rickard's actions posed a \"grave public safety risk\" and that the officers \"acted reasonably in using deadly force to end that risk\". The Court also found that the number of shots fired was also reasonable, writing that \"if police officers are justified in firing at a suspect in order to end a severe threat to public safety, the officers need not stop shooting until the threat has ended\". Finally, the Court found that even if the officers' conduct did violate the Fourth Amendment, they would still be entitled to summary judgment based on qualified immunity because their actions did not violate clearly established law at the time of the incident.\n\n== Background ==\n\n=== Prior case law ===\nThe [[Fourth Amendment to the United States Constitution]] prohibits unreasonable [[Search and seizure|searches and seizures]] by the federal government, and the [[Fourteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Fourteenth Amendment]] extends this prohibition to state governments under the [[Incorporation of the Bill of Rights|incorporation doctrine]]. In the course of their duties, police officers must sometimes make split-second decisions in situations where they believe there is a serious threat to the lives of themselves or the public. The [[use of force]] by police officers to counter such threats constitutes a seizure in the eyes of the Fourth Amendment. The Supreme Court has previously held in such cases as ''[[Tennessee v. Garner]]'' (1985) and ''[[Graham v. Connor]]'' (1989) that the use of force, including deadly force, by a police officer does not violate the Fourth Amendment if it is \"objectively reasonable\" in light of the circumstances confronting them.<ref>Ross, p. 246</ref>\n\nIn the past, the Supreme Court has also examined the use of force against fleeing motorists specifically. In ''[[Brosseau v. Haugen]]'' (2004), the Supreme Court upheld the use of force by a police officer who fired her gun into the back of a suspect's car after chasing the suspect on foot.<ref>Ross, p. 247\u201348</ref> The Court has also held in ''[[Scott v. Harris]]'' (2007) that a \"police officer's attempt to terminate a dangerous high-speed car chase that threatens the lives of innocent bystanders does not violate the Fourth Amendment, even when it places the fleeing motorist at risk of serious injury or death.\"<ref>''Scott v. Harris'', 550 U.S. 372 (2007), [https://www.supremecourt.gov/opinions/06pdf/05-1631.pdf slip op.] at 13 (U.S. April 30, 2007).</ref> In both cases, the Court confirmed that the standard of review for force against fleeing motorists is the same \"objective reasonableness\" standard as that in ''Graham v. Connor''.<ref>Ross, p. 248</ref>\n\nIf a person believes that the use of force against them is unjustified, [[42 U.S.C. \u00a71983]] allows them to file a civil action, claiming a violation of their constitutional rights. In general, police officers are protected from individual liability from these claims by the [[qualified immunity]] doctrine, which prevents government officials, including police officers, from being held individually liable for federal civil rights violations unless their conduct violated clearly established law at the time in question.<ref>Ross, p. 248</ref> In ''[[Johnson v. Jones]]'' (1995), the Supreme Court held that a defendant entitled to qualified immunity in these kinds of cases cannot immediately appeal a [[United States district court|district court]]'s order regarding a motion for [[summary judgment]] \"insofar as that order determines whether or not the pretrial record sets forth a genuine issue of fact for trial\".<ref>''Johnson v. Jones'', [https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/515/304/case.pdf 515 U.S. 304] (1995), (U.S. June 12, 1995).</ref>\n\n=== Facts of the case ===\nAt around midnight on July 18, 2004, a lieutenant of the [[West Memphis, Arkansas]], Police Department pulled over a white Honda Accord driven by Donald Rickard because the car had only one working headlight. There was also a passenger named Kelly Allen in the car's passenger seat. During the [[traffic stop]], the lieutenant asked Rickard to step out of the car because he appeared nervous and failed to produce a driver license when asked. Instead of doing so, Rickard decided to speed away from the officer. The lieutenant, later joined by other officers, pursued Rickard in a high-speed car chase down [[Interstate 40]], exceeding speeds over 100 miles per hour.<ref>''Plumhoff'', 572 U.S. ___ at 2.</ref> The entire chase lasted approximately five minutes. According to a video of the car chase, Rickard nearly struck 29 other drivers, struck two different patrol cars, and nearly struck another patrol car. Rickard drove east, crossing the Mississippi River into Tennessee. The officers attempted unsuccessfully to use a \"[[rolling roadblock]]\" to stop Rickard.<ref name=\":2\">Ross, p. 251.</ref>\n\nAfter exiting Interstate 40, Rickard collided with the cruiser of one of the officers and spun out into a parking lot in [[Memphis, Tennessee]].<ref name=\"plumhoff3\" /> After Rickard temporarily stopped next to a building, officers approached Rickard's car on foot; Rickard then began to back up, and an officer pounded against his passenger-side window with his firearm.<ref name=\":2\" /> Rickard then collided with another police cruiser, and even though Rickard's bumper was flush against the cruiser, he continued to use his accelerator. At this point, Sergeant Vance Plumhoff fired three shots into Rickard's car. Then, as Rickard continued \"fleeing down\" a street, officers fired twelve additional shots in the direction of Rickard's car, making the total number of shots fired in the incident fifteen. Rickard then lost control and crashed into a building. He and his passenger died from a combination of gunshot wounds and crash injuries.<ref name=\"plumhoff3\">''Plumhoff'', 572 U.S. ___ at 3.</ref>\n\n=== Lower court proceedings ===\n\nWhitne Rickard, Rickard's [[Minor (law)|minor]] daughter, filed a legal action under [[42 U.S.C. \u00a71983]] against Plumhoff and the other officers, as well as the chief of police and the mayor, alleging that the officers had violated the Fourth and Fourteenth Amendments by using excessive force against her father and his passenger.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\"plumhoff3\" /> The officers filed a motion for [[summary judgment]] on the basis of [[qualified immunity]]. The [[U.S. District Court for the Western District of Tennessee]] denied this motion, holding that the officers' conduct violated clearly established law at the time of the incident. Before the case could proceed, the officers appealed the district court's denial to the [[U.S. Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit]], which initially dismissed the appeal for lack of jurisdiction, citing the Supreme Court's decision in ''Johnson v. Jones'', but later vacated that judgment and instead affirmed the District Court's holding.<ref name=\"plumhoff4\">''Plumhoff'', 572 U.S. ___ at 4.</ref>\n\n== Supreme Court ==\n[[File:Samuel Alito official photo.jpg|thumb|Justice Samuel Alito wrote the unanimous opinion of the U.S. Supreme Court in ''Plumhoff v. Rickard'']]\nThe officers petitioned the case to the Supreme Court of the United States, which granted [[certiorari]] on November 15, 2013, in order to review two questions: (1) \"whether the Sixth Circuit wrongly denied qualified immunity to Petitioners by analyzing whether the force used in 2004 was distinguishable from factually similar force ruled permissible three years later in ''Scott v. Harris''\", and (2) \"whether the Sixth Circuit erred in denying qualified immunity by finding the use of force was not reasonable as a matter of law\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.supremecourt.gov/qp/12-01117qp.pdf|title=12-1117 Plumhoff v. Rickard: Question Presented|date=November 13, 2013|website=U.S. Supreme Court|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170411002552/https://www.supremecourt.gov/qp/12-01117qp.pdf|archive-date=April 11, 2017|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Opinion of the Court ===\nJustice [[Samuel Alito]] delivered the opinion of the Court on May 27, 2014. Writing for a unanimous Court,{{Efn|The Court's decision was unanimous (9\u20130) except that Justice [[Ruth Bader Ginsburg]] did not join parts III\u2013A and III\u2013B, and Justice [[Stephen Breyer]] did not join part III\u2013B\u20132.<ref>''Plumhoff'', 572 U.S. ___ at 1.</ref> The Supreme Court's opinion is divided as follows. \n* Part I describes the facts of the case and the lower court proceedings.\n* In Part II, the Court holds that it has jurisdiction to hear this case.\n* In Part III\u2013A, the Court explains why it was beginning its legal analysis with whether a constitutional right was actually violated.\n* In Part III\u2013B\u20131, the Court holds that the police did not violate the Fourth Amendment by using deadly force to end the high-speed car chase.\n* In Part III\u2013B\u20132, the Court rejects the argument that number of shots fired in this case was unreasonable, even if it was reasonable to use deadly force.\n* In Part III\u2013C, the Court holds that even if the officers' conduct did violate the Fourth Amendment, they \"would still be entitled to summary judgment based on qualified immunity\".|name=opinionbreakdown|group=}} Alito began by addressing whether the Supreme Court had jurisdiction to hear the case as an [[interlocutory appeal]].{{Efn|An [[interlocutory appeal]] is a type of appeal that occurs in the middle of a trial court's proceeding, while other aspects of the case are still pending. In the case of ''Plumhoff v. Rickard'', the police officers appealed the district court's order denying [[summary judgment]] on qualified immunity. Because the officers appealed the case immediately after this order, without waiting for the case to proceed to trial, the appeal is considered \"interlocutory\".}} In general, federal law (specifically 28 U.S.C. \u00a71291) only allows courts of appeals to hear appeals from the \"final decisions\" of district courts, and Alito acknowledged that an order denying summary judgment \"is generally not a final decision within the meaning of \u00a71291 and is thus generally not immediately appealable\".<ref name=\":0\">''Plumhoff'', 572 U.S. ___ at 5.</ref> However, summary judgments based on qualified immunity are an exception to this general rule, since qualified immunity is \"an immunity from suit rather than a mere defense to liability\".<ref name=\":0\" /> Alito rejected the respondent's argument that the Court's decision in ''Johnson v. Jones'' prevents Court from having jurisdiction in this case, stating that in ''Johnson'', the summary judgment order was not appealable because \"it merely decided 'a question of evidence sufficiency', ''i.e.'' which facts a party may, or may not, be able to prove at trial\".<ref>''Plumhoff'', 572 U.S. ___ at 6.</ref> In the case of ''Plumhoff v. Jones'', however, the officers raised legal issues, and Alito stated that \"deciding legal issues of this sort is a core responsibility of appellate courts\".<ref>''Plumhoff'', 572 U.S. ___ at 6\u20137.</ref>\n\nMoving onto the legal questions, Alito first explained why he was beginning his analysis of whether the officers' violated \"clearly established law\" by first answering whether the officers' actually violated the Fourth Amendment's prohibition against unreasonable seizures, citing the Court's decision in ''[[Saucier v. Katz]]'' (2001).<ref>''Plumhoff'', 572 U.S. ___ at 7.</ref> Examining the facts of the case \"from the perspective 'of a reasonable officer on the scene, rather than with 20/20 vision of hindsight'\", Alito concluded that the officers had acted reasonably and had not violated the Fourth Amendment.<ref>''Plumhoff'', 572 U.S. ___ at 8\u201310.</ref> Alito wrote there was \"no basis for reach a different conclusion\" from the Court's decision in ''Scott v. Harris'', stating that \"Rickard's outrageously reckless driving posed a grave public safety risk\".<ref>''Plumhoff'', 572 U.S. ___ at 10.</ref> Furthermore, Alito rejected the respondent's argument that even if the officers were justified in using deadly force, the degree of force that the officers used when firing 15 shots into Rickard's car was unreasonable, writing that \"if police officers are justified in firing at a suspect in order to end a severe threat to public safety, the officers need not stop shooting until the threat has ended\".<ref name=\":1\">''Plumhoff'', 572 U.S. ___ at 11.</ref> The presence of a passenger in Rickard's car does not affect this analysis because the question in the case is \"whether petitioners violated Rickard\u2019s Fourth Amendment rights, not Allen\u2019s\".<ref name=\":1\" /> Finally, Alito wrote that even if the officers' conduct had violated the Fourth Amendment, they \"would still be entitled to summary judgment based on qualified immunity\".<ref>''Plumhoff'', 572 U.S. ___ at 12.</ref>\n\n== Analysis and reception ==\n\n=== Implications ===\n\nIn a legal analysis published in ''[[Criminal Justice Review]]'', a peer-reviewed academic journal published by [[SAGE Publishing]], Darrell L. Ross of [[Valdosta State University]] discussed the legal and practical implications of ''Plumhoff''. According to Ross, \"lower courts are reminded of how to assess issues pertaining to qualified immunity, particularly in use of force cases\".<ref name=\":3\">Ross p. 254</ref> Specifically, the \"correct standard, as reiterated by the Court\u2014which was never discussed by the Sixth Circuit\u2014is whether the right was sufficiently clear that every reasonable official would have understood what he or she is doing violates that right.\"<ref name=\":3\" /> Additionally, Ross wrote that police are also reminded of the Court's principles regarding the use of deadly force in accordance with ''Graham'', especially as it pertains to fleeing motorists. Specifically, Ross wrote, \"Whether force appears reasonable is measured from the perspective of the officer at the moment the officer decided to use it.\"<ref name=\":3\" /> Ross also emphasized the implications of the Court's analysis over the number of rounds fired. Ross commented that police officers \"are not trained or required to shoot to wound, nor are they trained to shoot warning shots prior to responding with deadly force.\"<ref name=\":4\">Ross, p. 255</ref> According to Ross, \"Justice Alito confirmed the fact officers are trained to keep shooting until the threat is stopped ...\"<ref name=\":4\" /> Finally, Ross wrote, \"Police administrators are encouraged to review and revise their current use of force and pursuit policies consistent with this decision.\"<ref name=\":4\" /> Ross recommended that \"administrators should provide training to their officers on use of force legal issues and principles that emerge from ''Rickard'', ''Graham'', ''Scott'', and ''Brosseau''\".<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n=== Reactions and criticism ===\n\n[[Erwin Chemerinsky]], the dean of the [[University of California, Irvine School of Law]], wrote an opinion piece published in ''[[The New York Times]]'', in which he described the Court's decision as \"deeply disturbing\", arguing that there are alternatives to shooting at vehicles involves in high-speed car chases and that the Court has \"weakened accountability by ruling that a local government can be held liable only if it is proved that the city\u2019s or county\u2019s own policy violated the Constitution\".<ref name=\"nyt\">{{cite news |last1=Chemerinsky |first1=Erwin |title=Opinion {{!}} How the Supreme Court Protects Bad Cops |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/08/27/opinion/how-the-supreme-court-protects-bad-cops.html |accessdate=30 November 2019 |work=The New York Times |publisher=The New York Times |date=26 August 2014 |page=A23}}</ref> In the article, Chemerinsky also opposed the doctrine of qualified immunity, arguing that it poses an unreasonable burden for individuals alleging violations of constitutional rights.<ref name=\"nyt\" /> In a blog post published in ''[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]'', Jonathan R. Nash, a professor of law at [[Emory University School of Law]], argued that the Court's decision in ''Plumhoff'' was inconsistent with the precedent it set in ''Scott'', commenting that the Court \"jettisoned ''Scott''<nowiki/>'s careful balancing in favor of an approach designed to give the police substantial leeway in terminating chases\".<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/blogs/pundits-blog/the-judiciary/215291-high-speed-police-pursuits-and-deadly-force|title=High-speed police pursuits and deadly force|last=Nash|first=Jonathan R.|date=August 19, 2014|website=The Hill|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180414175726/https://thehill.com/blogs/pundits-blog/the-judiciary/215291-high-speed-police-pursuits-and-deadly-force|archive-date=April 14, 2018|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref> Nash stated there were differences between the facts in ''Plumhoff'' versus the facts in ''Scott'', which he felt should have compelled the Court to a different conclusion. For example, in ''Scott'', the police used a maneuver that caused the driver to spin out of control, whereas in ''Plumhoff'', the police used their firearms. Additionally, in ''Scott'', the driver was the only one in the fleeing car, whereas in ''Plumhoff'', Rickard had a passenger.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n== Footnotes ==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n; Sources\n* ''Plumhoff v. Rickard'', 572 U.S. ___ (2014), [https://www.supremecourt.gov/opinions/13pdf/12-1117_1bn5.pdf slip op.] (U.S. May 27, 2014).\n* {{cite journal |last1=Ross |first1=Darrell L. |title=Plumhoff v. Rickard: Clarifying the Use of Deadly Force and Qualified Immunity |journal=Criminal Justice Review |date=June 2015 |volume=40 |issue=2 |pages=244-257 |doi=10.1177/0734016814543353 |publisher=SAGE Publishing}}\n\n; References\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{caselaw source\n | case = ''Plumhoff v. Rickard''\n | googlescholar = https://scholar.google.com/scholar_case?case=17750181401591044185\n | justia =https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/572/12-1117/\n | oyez =https://www.oyez.org/cases/2013/12-1117\n | other_source1 = Supreme Court (slip opinion)\n | other_url1 =https://www.supremecourt.gov/opinions/13pdf/12-1117_1bn5.pdf\n }}\n* [https://www.scotusblog.com/case-files/cases/plumhoff-v-rickard/ SCOTUS blog]\n* {{Coord|35|9|22.7|N|90|2|13.4|W}} \u2013 the parking lot where Rickard's car spun out (via [https://www.oyez.org/cases/2013/12-1117 Oyez])\n\n{{US4thAmendment|seizures|state=expanded}}\n\n[[Category:United States Supreme Court cases]]\n[[Category:United States Supreme Court cases of the Roberts Court]]\n[[Category:United States Fourth Amendment case law]]\n[[Category:2014 in United States case law]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox SCOTUS case\n| Litigants = Plumoff v. Rickard\n| ArgueDate = March 4\n| ArgueYear = 2014\n| DecideDate = May 27\n| DecideYear = 2014\n| FullName = Officer Vance Plumhoff, et al., v. Whitne Rickard, a minor child, individually, and as surviving daughter of Donald Rickard, deceased, by and through her mother, Samantha Rickard, as parent and next friend\n| USVol = 572\n| USPage = ___\n| ParallelCitations = \n| Docket = 12-1117\n| OralArgument = https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/roberts6/oral_argument_audio/23632\n| OralReargument = \n| OpinionAnnouncement = https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/roberts6/opinion_announcement_audio/23622\n| Prior = \n| Subsequent = \n| Holding = (1) The [[Sixth Circuit]] properly exercised jurisdiction under 28 U. S. C. \u00a71291. The general rule that an order denying a summary judgment motion is not a \"final decision\", and thus not immediately appealable, does not apply when it is based on a qualified immunity claim. (2) The officers' conduct did not violate the [[Fourth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Fourth Amendment]].\n| SCOTUS = \n| Majority = Alito\n| JoinMajority = ''unanimous'' except Ginsburg as to parts III\u2013A and III\u2013B and Breyer as to part III\u2013B\u20132{{efn|name=opinionbreakdown}}\n| Concurrence = \n| JoinConcurrence = \n| Concurrence2 = \n| JoinConcurrence2 = \n| Concurrence/Dissent = \n| JoinConcurrence/Dissent = \n| Dissent = \n| JoinDissent = \n| Dissent2 = \n| JoinDissent2 = \n| LawsApplied = [[Fourth Amendment to the United States Constitution|U.S. Const. amend. IV]]\n}}\n\n'''''Plumhoff v. Rickard''''', 572 U.S. ___ (2014), is a [[Supreme Court of the United States|United States Supreme Court]] case involving the [[use of force]] by [[police officer]]s during high-speed [[car chase]]s. After first holding that it had [[jurisdiction]] to hear the case, the Court held that the conduct of the police officers involved in the case did not violate the [[Fourth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Fourth Amendment to the U.S. Constitution]], which prohibits unreasonable [[Search and seizure|searches and seizures]].\n\nAt midnight on July 18, 2004, Donald Rickard led police officers on a high-speed car chase which ended in a parking lot, where officers fired fifteen shots into Rickard's car. Rickard and his passenger both died from a combination of gunshot wounds and injuries sustained when the car eventually crashed. Rickard's daughter sued the officers who shot Rickard, arguing that they had used [[excessive force]] in violation of the Fourth Amendment. The officers moved for [[summary judgment]] based on [[qualified immunity]] because they believed their actions did not violate clearly established law at the time of the car chase. The district court denied this motion, and the court of appeals affirmed.\n\nOn May 27, 2014, the Supreme Court reversed, holding that the officers did not violate the Fourth Amendment. In a unanimous (9\u20130) decision authored by [[Justice Samuel Alito]],{{efn|name=opinionbreakdown}} the Court found that Rickard's actions posed a \"grave public safety risk\" and that the officers \"acted reasonably in using deadly force to end that risk\". The Court also found that the number of shots fired was also reasonable, writing that \"if police officers are justified in firing at a suspect in order to end a severe threat to public safety, the officers need not stop shooting until the threat has ended\". Finally, the Court found that even if the officers' conduct did violate the Fourth Amendment, they would still be entitled to summary judgment based on qualified immunity because their actions did not violate clearly established law at the time of the incident.\n\n== Background ==\n\n=== Prior case law ===\nThe [[Fourth Amendment to the United States Constitution]] prohibits unreasonable [[Search and seizure|searches and seizures]] by the federal government, and the [[Fourteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Fourteenth Amendment]] extends this prohibition to state governments under the [[Incorporation of the Bill of Rights|incorporation doctrine]]. In the course of their duties, police officers must sometimes make split-second decisions in situations where they believe there is a serious threat to the lives of themselves or the public. The [[use of force]] by police officers to counter such threats constitutes a seizure in the eyes of the Fourth Amendment. The Supreme Court has previously held in such cases as ''[[Tennessee v. Garner]]'' (1985) and ''[[Graham v. Connor]]'' (1989) that the use of force, including deadly force, by a police officer does not violate the Fourth Amendment if it is \"objectively reasonable\" in light of the circumstances confronting them.<ref>Ross, p. 246</ref>\n\nIn the past, the Supreme Court has also examined the use of force against fleeing motorists specifically. In ''[[Brosseau v. Haugen]]'' (2004), the Supreme Court upheld the use of force by a police officer who fired her gun into the back of a suspect's car after chasing the suspect on foot.<ref>Ross, p. 247\u201348</ref> In the U.S. Supreme Court has also held in ''[[Scott v. Harris]]'' (2007) that a \"police officer's attempt to terminate a dangerous high-speed car chase that threatens the lives of innocent bystanders does not violate the Fourth Amendment, even when it places the fleeing motorist at risk of serious injury or death.\"<ref>''Scott v. Harris'', 550 U.S. 372 (2007), [https://www.supremecourt.gov/opinions/06pdf/05-1631.pdf slip op.] at 13 (U.S. April 30, 2007).</ref> In both cases, the Court confirmed that the standard of review for force against fleeing motorists is the same \"objective reasonableness\" standard as that in ''Graham v. Connor''.<ref>Ross, p. 248</ref>\n\nIf a person believes that the use of force against them is unjustified, [[42 U.S.C. \u00a71983]] allows them to file a civil action, claiming a violation of their constitutional rights. In general, police officers are protected from individual liability from these claims by the [[qualified immunity]] doctrine, which prevents government officials, including police officers, from being held individually liable for federal civil rights violations unless their conduct violated clearly established law at the time in question.<ref>Ross, p. 248</ref> In ''[[Johnson v. Jones]]'' (1995), the Supreme Court held that a defendant entitled to qualified immunity in these kinds of cases cannot immediately appeal a [[United States district court|district court]]'s order regarding a motion for [[summary judgment]] \"insofar as that order determines whether or not the pretrial record sets forth a genuine issue of fact for trial\".<ref>''Johnson v. Jones'', [https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/515/304/case.pdf 515 U.S. 304] (1995), (U.S. June 12, 1995).</ref>\n\n=== Facts of the case ===\nAt around midnight on July 18, 2004, a lieutenant of the [[West Memphis, Arkansas]], Police Department pulled over a white Honda Accord driven by Donald Rickard because the car had only one working headlight. There was also a passenger named Kelly Allen in the car's passenger seat. During the [[traffic stop]], the lieutenant asked Rickard to step out of the car because he appeared nervous and failed to produce a driver license when asked. Instead of doing so, Rickard decided to speed away from the officer. The lieutenant, later joined by other officers, pursued Rickard in a high-speed car chase down [[Interstate 40]], exceeding speeds over 100 miles per hour.<ref>''Plumhoff'', 572 U.S. ___ at 2.</ref> The entire chase lasted approximately five minutes. According to a video of the car chase, Rickard nearly struck 29 other drivers, struck two different patrol cars, and nearly struck another patrol car. Rickard drove east, crossing the Mississippi River into Tennessee. The officers attempted unsuccessfully to use a \"[[rolling roadblock]]\" to stop Rickard.<ref name=\":2\">Ross, p. 251.</ref>\n\nAfter exiting Interstate 40, Rickard collided with the cruiser of one of the officers and spun out into a parking lot in [[Memphis, Tennessee]].<ref name=\"plumhoff3\" /> After Rickard temporarily stopped next to a building, officers approached Rickard's car on foot; Rickard then began to back up, and an officer pounded against his passenger-side window with his firearm.<ref name=\":2\" /> Rickard then collided with another police cruiser, and even though Rickard's bumper was flush against the cruiser, he continued to use his accelerator. At this point, Sergeant Vance Plumhoff fired three shots into Rickard's car. Then, as Rickard continued \"fleeing down\" a street, officers fired twelve additional shots in the direction of Rickard's car, making the total number of shots fired in the incident fifteen. Rickard then lost control and crashed into a building. He and his passenger died from a combination of gunshot wounds and crash injuries.<ref name=\"plumhoff3\">''Plumhoff'', 572 U.S. ___ at 3.</ref>\n\n=== Lower court proceedings ===\n\nWhitne Rickard, Rickard's [[Minor (law)|minor]] daughter, filed a legal action under [[42 U.S.C. \u00a71983]] against Plumhoff and the other officers, as well as the chief of police and the mayor, alleging that the officers had violated the Fourth and Fourteenth Amendments by using excessive force against her father and his passenger.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\"plumhoff3\" /> The officers filed a motion for [[summary judgment]] on the basis of [[qualified immunity]]. The [[U.S. District Court for the Western District of Tennessee]] denied this motion, holding that the officers' conduct violated clearly established law at the time of the incident. Before the case could proceed, the officers appealed the district court's denial to the [[U.S. Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit]], which initially dismissed the appeal for lack of jurisdiction, citing the Supreme Court's decision in ''Johnson v. Jones'', but later vacated that judgment and instead affirmed the District Court's holding.<ref name=\"plumhoff4\">''Plumhoff'', 572 U.S. ___ at 4.</ref>\n\n== Supreme Court ==\n[[File:Samuel Alito official photo.jpg|thumb|Justice Samuel Alito wrote the unanimous opinion of the U.S. Supreme Court in ''Plumhoff v. Rickard'']]\nThe officers petitioned the case to the Supreme Court of the United States, which granted [[certiorari]] on November 15, 2013, in order to review two questions: (1) \"whether the Sixth Circuit wrongly denied qualified immunity to Petitioners by analyzing whether the force used in 2004 was distinguishable from factually similar force ruled permissible three years later in ''Scott v. Harris''\", and (2) \"whether the Sixth Circuit erred in denying qualified immunity by finding the use of force was not reasonable as a matter of law\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.supremecourt.gov/qp/12-01117qp.pdf|title=12-1117 Plumhoff v. Rickard: Question Presented|date=November 13, 2013|website=U.S. Supreme Court|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170411002552/https://www.supremecourt.gov/qp/12-01117qp.pdf|archive-date=April 11, 2017|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Opinion of the Court ===\nJustice [[Samuel Alito]] delivered the opinion of the Court on May 27, 2014. Writing for a unanimous Court,{{Efn|The Court's decision was unanimous (9\u20130) except that Justice [[Ruth Bader Ginsburg]] did not join parts III\u2013A and III\u2013B, and Justice [[Stephen Breyer]] did not join part III\u2013B\u20132.<ref>''Plumhoff'', 572 U.S. ___ at 1.</ref> The Supreme Court's opinion is divided as follows. \n* Part I describes the facts of the case and the lower court proceedings.\n* In Part II, the Court holds that it has jurisdiction to hear this case.\n* In Part III\u2013A, the Court explains why it was beginning its legal analysis with whether a constitutional right was actually violated.\n* In Part III\u2013B\u20131, the Court holds that the police did not violate the Fourth Amendment by using deadly force to end the high-speed car chase.\n* In Part III\u2013B\u20132, the Court rejects the argument that number of shots fired in this case was unreasonable, even if it was reasonable to use deadly force.\n* In Part III\u2013C, the Court holds that even if the officers' conduct did violate the Fourth Amendment, they \"would still be entitled to summary judgment based on qualified immunity\".|name=opinionbreakdown|group=}} Alito began by addressing whether the Supreme Court had jurisdiction to hear the case as an [[interlocutory appeal]].{{Efn|An [[interlocutory appeal]] is a type of appeal that occurs in the middle of a trial court's proceeding, while other aspects of the case are still pending. In the case of ''Plumhoff v. Rickard'', the police officers appealed the district court's order denying [[summary judgment]] on qualified immunity. Because the officers appealed the case immediately after this order, without waiting for the case to proceed to trial, the appeal is considered \"interlocutory\".}} In general, federal law (specifically 28 U.S.C. \u00a71291) only allows courts of appeals to hear appeals from the \"final decisions\" of district courts, and Alito acknowledged that an order denying summary judgment \"is generally not a final decision within the meaning of \u00a71291 and is thus generally not immediately appealable\".<ref name=\":0\">''Plumhoff'', 572 U.S. ___ at 5.</ref> However, summary judgments based on qualified immunity are an exception to this general rule, since qualified immunity is \"an immunity from suit rather than a mere defense to liability\".<ref name=\":0\" /> Alito rejected the respondent's argument that the Court's decision in ''Johnson v. Jones'' prevents Court from having jurisdiction in this case, stating that in ''Johnson'', the summary judgment order was not appealable because \"it merely decided 'a question of evidence sufficiency', ''i.e.'' which facts a party may, or may not, be able to prove at trial\".<ref>''Plumhoff'', 572 U.S. ___ at 6.</ref> In the case of ''Plumhoff v. Jones'', however, the officers raised legal issues, and Alito stated that \"deciding legal issues of this sort is a core responsibility of appellate courts\".<ref>''Plumhoff'', 572 U.S. ___ at 6\u20137.</ref>\n\nMoving onto the legal questions, Alito first explained why he was beginning his analysis of whether the officers' violated \"clearly established law\" by first answering whether the officers' actually violated the Fourth Amendment's prohibition against unreasonable seizures, citing the Court's decision in ''[[Saucier v. Katz]]'' (2001).<ref>''Plumhoff'', 572 U.S. ___ at 7.</ref> Examining the facts of the case \"from the perspective 'of a reasonable officer on the scene, rather than with 20/20 vision of hindsight'\", Alito concluded that the officers had acted reasonably and had not violated the Fourth Amendment.<ref>''Plumhoff'', 572 U.S. ___ at 8\u201310.</ref> Alito wrote there was \"no basis for reach a different conclusion\" from the Court's decision in ''Scott v. Harris'', stating that \"Rickard's outrageously reckless driving posed a grave public safety risk\".<ref>''Plumhoff'', 572 U.S. ___ at 10.</ref> Furthermore, Alito rejected the respondent's argument that even if the officers were justified in using deadly force, the degree of force that the officers used when firing 15 shots into Rickard's car was unreasonable, writing that \"if police officers are justified in firing at a suspect in order to end a severe threat to public safety, the officers need not stop shooting until the threat has ended\".<ref name=\":1\">''Plumhoff'', 572 U.S. ___ at 11.</ref> The presence of a passenger in Rickard's car does not affect this analysis because the question in the case is \"whether petitioners violated Rickard\u2019s Fourth Amendment rights, not Allen\u2019s\".<ref name=\":1\" /> Finally, Alito wrote that even if the officers' conduct had violated the Fourth Amendment, they \"would still be entitled to summary judgment based on qualified immunity\".<ref>''Plumhoff'', 572 U.S. ___ at 12.</ref>\n\n== Analysis and reception ==\n\n=== Implications ===\n\nIn a legal analysis published in ''[[Criminal Justice Review]]'', a peer-reviewed academic journal published by [[SAGE Publishing]], Darrell L. Ross of [[Valdosta State University]] discussed the legal and practical implications of ''Plumhoff''. According to Ross, \"lower courts are reminded of how to assess issues pertaining to qualified immunity, particularly in use of force cases\".<ref name=\":3\">Ross p. 254</ref> Specifically, the \"correct standard, as reiterated by the Court\u2014which was never discussed by the Sixth Circuit\u2014is whether the right was sufficiently clear that every reasonable official would have understood what he or she is doing violates that right.\"<ref name=\":3\" /> Additionally, Ross wrote that police are also reminded of the Court's principles regarding the use of deadly force in accordance with ''Graham'', especially as it pertains to fleeing motorists. Specifically, Ross wrote, \"Whether force appears reasonable is measured from the perspective of the officer at the moment the officer decided to use it.\"<ref name=\":3\" /> Ross also emphasized the implications of the Court's analysis over the number of rounds fired. Ross commented that police officers \"are not trained or required to shoot to wound, nor are they trained to shoot warning shots prior to responding with deadly force.\"<ref name=\":4\">Ross, p. 255</ref> According to Ross, \"Justice Alito confirmed the fact officers are trained to keep shooting until the threat is stopped ...\"<ref name=\":4\" /> Finally, Ross wrote, \"Police administrators are encouraged to review and revise their current use of force and pursuit policies consistent with this decision.\"<ref name=\":4\" /> Ross recommended that \"administrators should provide training to their officers on use of force legal issues and principles that emerge from ''Rickard'', ''Graham'', ''Scott'', and ''Brosseau''\".<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n=== Reactions and criticism ===\n\n[[Erwin Chemerinsky]], the dean of the [[University of California, Irvine School of Law]], wrote an opinion piece published in ''[[The New York Times]]'', in which he described the Court's decision as \"deeply disturbing\", arguing that there are alternatives to shooting at vehicles involves in high-speed car chases and that the Court has \"weakened accountability by ruling that a local government can be held liable only if it is proved that the city\u2019s or county\u2019s own policy violated the Constitution\".<ref name=\"nyt\">{{cite news |last1=Chemerinsky |first1=Erwin |title=Opinion {{!}} How the Supreme Court Protects Bad Cops |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/08/27/opinion/how-the-supreme-court-protects-bad-cops.html |accessdate=30 November 2019 |work=The New York Times |publisher=The New York Times |date=26 August 2014 |page=A23}}</ref> In the article, Chemerinsky also opposed the doctrine of qualified immunity, arguing that it poses an unreasonable burden for individuals alleging violations of constitutional rights.<ref name=\"nyt\" /> In a blog post published in ''[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]'', Jonathan R. Nash, a professor of law at [[Emory University School of Law]], argued that the Court's decision in ''Plumhoff'' was inconsistent with the precedent it set in ''Scott'', commenting that the Court \"jettisoned ''Scott''<nowiki/>'s careful balancing in favor of an approach designed to give the police substantial leeway in terminating chases\".<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/blogs/pundits-blog/the-judiciary/215291-high-speed-police-pursuits-and-deadly-force|title=High-speed police pursuits and deadly force|last=Nash|first=Jonathan R.|date=August 19, 2014|website=The Hill|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180414175726/https://thehill.com/blogs/pundits-blog/the-judiciary/215291-high-speed-police-pursuits-and-deadly-force|archive-date=April 14, 2018|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref> Nash stated there were differences between the facts in ''Plumhoff'' versus the facts in ''Scott'', which he felt should have compelled the Court to a different conclusion. For example, in ''Scott'', the police used a maneuver that caused the driver to spin out of control, whereas in ''Plumhoff'', the police used their firearms. Additionally, in ''Scott'', the driver was the only one in the fleeing car, whereas in ''Plumhoff'', Rickard had a passenger.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n== Footnotes ==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n; Sources\n* ''Plumhoff v. Rickard'', 572 U.S. ___ (2014), [https://www.supremecourt.gov/opinions/13pdf/12-1117_1bn5.pdf slip op.] (U.S. May 27, 2014).\n* {{cite journal |last1=Ross |first1=Darrell L. |title=Plumhoff v. Rickard: Clarifying the Use of Deadly Force and Qualified Immunity |journal=Criminal Justice Review |date=June 2015 |volume=40 |issue=2 |pages=244-257 |doi=10.1177/0734016814543353 |publisher=SAGE Publishing}}\n\n; References\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{caselaw source\n | case = ''Plumhoff v. Rickard''\n | googlescholar = https://scholar.google.com/scholar_case?case=17750181401591044185\n | justia =https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/572/12-1117/\n | oyez =https://www.oyez.org/cases/2013/12-1117\n | other_source1 = Supreme Court (slip opinion)\n | other_url1 =https://www.supremecourt.gov/opinions/13pdf/12-1117_1bn5.pdf\n }}\n* [https://www.scotusblog.com/case-files/cases/plumhoff-v-rickard/ SCOTUS blog]\n* {{Coord|35|9|22.7|N|90|2|13.4|W}} \u2013 the parking lot where Rickard's car spun out (via [https://www.oyez.org/cases/2013/12-1117 Oyez])\n\n{{US4thAmendment|seizures|state=expanded}}\n\n[[Category:United States Supreme Court cases]]\n[[Category:United States Supreme Court cases of the Roberts Court]]\n[[Category:United States Fourth Amendment case law]]\n[[Category:2014 in United States case law]]\n", "name_user": "Mz7", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePrior case law:typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plumhoff_v._Rickard"}
